item.description:
Partial Ordering Relation # A [[Math/Discrete Mathematics/Relation/Relation#Relation|relation]] R is said to be a partial order relation if R is:
[[Math/Discrete Mathematics/Relation/Reflexive Relation|Reflexive]] [[Math/Discrete Mathematics/Relation/Antisymmetric Relation|Antisymmetric]] [[Math/Discrete Mathematics/Relation/Transitive Relation|Transitive]] Partially Ordered Set (POSET) # A set &lsquo;A&rsquo; with partially ordering relation &lsquo;R&rsquo; defined on &lsquo;A&rsquo; is called POSET. Denoted by &ldquo;[A;R]&rdquo;
Example # If &lsquo;A&rsquo; is any set of real numbers then [A;&lt;=] is a POSET cuz it is reflexive, antisymmetric &amp; transitive.

Cartesian Product # Cartesian product of A and B: A×B={(a,b) ; a∈A,b∈B}
Example # A={a,b} and B={1,2,3} then A×B = {(a,1),(a,2),(a,3),(b,1),(b,2),(b,3)}
Property # If |A|=m and |B|=n then |A×B|=mn
Relation # Let A, B be two sets. Every relation, then, from A to B is a subset of A×B. Relation R⊆A×B.
Number of Relations possible # Using the [[#Property]], and by definition of a relation the number of relations from A to B: = [[Math/Discrete Mathematics/Power Set#Number of elements in Power Set|number of subsets]] of |A×B| = 2ᵐⁿ
